    explanation: `The presentation is most consistent with a diagnosis of cataract, a term used for any lens opacity. The prevalence of cataracts increases with age. Sixty-five per cent of those aged 50 to 59 and all people older than 80 will have lens opacities. Cataracts present with gradual loss of vision with preserved direct pupillary light reflex. Unilateral cataracts may remain unnoticed, but the mono-ocular impaired vision may affect distance judgment due to stereopsis. Bilateral cataracts lead to gradual vision loss that can cause frequent changes in glasses. Dazzling, especially in sunlight, is initially seen. With bilateral cataracts, difficulty reading, recognising faces, watching TV, and driving, particularly at night, becomes the more prominent symptom. Appearance of the lens in a patient with cataract is shown in the image. Option B: Chronic glaucoma presents with gradual loss of vision, often starting with blurring in the periphery of the visual field and progressing to involve the central vision. Dazzling is not a problem. Option C: Hypertensive retinopathy leads to vision loss and retinal hemorrhage, but dazzling is an unusual feature. Option D: Presbyopia is associated with aging and is characterised by the progressively diminishing ability to focus clearly on an object close to the eye. The first symptom of presbyopia is eyestrain. Others include difficulty seeing in dim light, problems focusing on small objects, and fine print. Presbyopia is usually noticed between the ages of 40 and 50. There is no dazzling. Option E: Retinal detachment is associated with floaters and flashes but is not dazzling.`,
