    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The clinical presentation and eye appearance make episcleritis the most likely diagnosis. Episcleritis is the inflammation of the episclera, the tissue between the conjunctiva and the sclera. The condition is usually mild and self-limiting but often recurrent. Two-thirds of the cases are idiopathic, and the remaining one-third can have an underlying systemic condition such as infections (tuberculosis, syphilis, Lyme disease or cat scratch disease) or a rheumatologic disorder (e.g. rheumatoid arthritis, polyarteritis nodosa, seronegative spondyloarthropathies, etc.). In patients with episcleritis, visual acuity and fields are unaffected. Mild photophobia and lacrimation might exist; however, these are not significant findings in most patients. The initial management usually starts with artificial lubricants (tears) such as Hypomellose or Artelac 4 to 6 times a day. For more discomfort and irritation not responsive to this measure, topical NSAIDs such as diclofenac would be the next line of treatment. Topical corticosteroids are reserved for those not responding to the above. Over 80% of the patients will respond to topical corticosteroids. Option A and C: No itchiness or discharge excludes allergic conjunctivitis; therefore, applying medications for allergies is unnecessary. Ketotifen is an antihistamine, and sodium cromoglycate is a mast cell inhibitor. These drugs have no role in managing episcleritis. Option D: Prednisolone can be a choice if the condition does not show a satisfactory response to artificial tear drops and topical NSAIDs. Option E: Chloramphenicol is an antibiotic used for the treatment of bacterial conjunctivitis. The absence of purulent discharge and/or sticky eyelids, especially when waking up, excludes bacterial conjunctivitis. NOTE – A distinction between episcleritis and scleritis is very important because while the former is a mild self-limiting condition, the latter can damage the eye and sight. Unlike episcleritis, scleritis is associated with severe penetrating eye pain radiating to the jaw, eyebrows, forehead, or sinuses. Eyeball tenderness is also characteristic of scleritis and is absent in episcleritis. Scleritis is almost always associated with an underlying systemic disease. In scleritis, redness increases gradually over several days. There is a bluish-red tinge which is best seen in the natural light rather than through the slit lamp. The discolouration can be focal or involve the entire sclera. The interpalpebral area is the most common site. The discolouration does not blanch with the application of sympathomimetic dilating drugs.`,
