    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Ear pain (otalgia) is a common complaint comprising approximately 4% of general practice encounters. The nerve supply for sensation in the ear originates from several cranial nerves (CN-V, CN-VII, CN-IX, CN-X) and cervical plexus branches (C2, C3). These nerves also supply multiple head and neck structures, so ear pain is often referred from elsewhere. Primary otalgia originates from ear structures themselves, while secondary otalgia is referred pain from other structures. In children, primary otalgia is more common; in adults, secondary causes are often responsible. Given this patient's age, normal ear examination, heavy smoking history (50 years), and lack of clues for other secondary causes of ear pain, squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue is the most likely explanation. Oropharyngeal neoplasms (soft palate, posterior pharyngeal wall, palatine tonsil, tongue base) can present with deep, intense otalgia. Patients may have additional symptoms of dysphagia, odynophagia, and sore throat, or may be asymptomatic. Risk factors include chronic alcohol use and tobacco exposure. Option A (Cholesteatoma): Consists of squamous epithelium trapped within the skull base; can erode structures and cause CNS complications. Hearing loss is common; large cholesteatomas fill the middle ear with desquamated epithelium and mucopurulent discharge, interfering with sound transmission and causing conductive hearing loss. Normal exam findings are inconsistent with cholesteatoma. Option B (Chronic otitis media): Presents with purulent ear discharge and conductive hearing loss. Otoscopy shows perforated tympanic membrane and pus in the ear canal. This patient has none of these findings. Option D (Acoustic neuroma): Intracranial tumors arising from the Schwann cell sheath of the vestibular or cochlear nerve. Unilateral hearing loss is the most common symptom at diagnosis. Other symptoms include headaches and imbalance. Absence of unilateral hearing loss and ear pain rather than headache make this diagnosis very unlikely. Option E (Ramsay-Hunt syndrome): Herpes zoster oticus; viral infection of the facial nerve presenting with ear pain, vesicles involving pinna/external auditory meatus, and facial nerve palsy. Absence of vesicles and other features of facial nerve involvement make this diagnosis unlikely.`,
