    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `The photograph shows a red eye with an elliptical iris and, more importantly, a deposit of white matter in the anterior chamber. These, alongside eye pain, photophobia, and blurred vision, make anterior uveitis the most likely diagnosis. The uvea is the pigmented eye part, including the iris, ciliary body, and choroid. The iris and ciliary body are called the anterior uvea. Iris inflammation invariably involves the ciliary body, too, so the inflammation is best referred to as anterior uveitis rather than iritis. Anterior uveitis is idiopathic in 50% of cases. The remaining half are caused by an underlying condition such as seronegative spondyloarthropathies, Behçet disease, Lyme disease, tuberculosis, sarcoidosis, herpes simplex and herpes zoster infections, juvenile rheumatic arthritis disease, or trauma. Clinical features suggestive of anterior uveitis include the following: Red eye: the redness in anterior uveitis is circumcorneal, meaning that there is a 360° injection around the limbus. The injection has the highest intensity in the peri limbus and decreases towards the periphery. The injection in conjunctivitis is reversed. Pain, Blurred vision, Photophobia (both direct and consensual) on examination, Constricted pupil – there might be pupil irregularities due to the adhesion of the iris to the anterior aspect of the lens, Lacrimation. Anterior uveitis can also be a complication of cataracts or other eye surgeries. Currently, phacoemulsification is the standard procedure for lens replacement in people with cataracts. This procedure is associated with some complications, with anterior uveitis being one of them. The eye illustrated in the photograph has a collection of exudate material at the bottom of the anterior chamber due to gravity, namely hypopyon, a feature seen in anterior uveitis. Option A (Hypopyon): Hypopyon is the accumulation of leukocytic exudate in the anterior chamber. The exudate settles at the dependent aspect of the eye due to gravity. Although this patient has hypopyon in the affected eye, this is a sign seen in anterior uveitis, not a diagnosis itself.`,
