    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The unilateral erythema and tender swelling shown in the photograph are characteristic of acute sialadenitis in the setting of salivary duct calculi. Salivary duct calculi are composed predominantly of calcium salts and form due to stasis and ductal inflammation. More than 80% of salivary duct stones occur in the submandibular gland due to its long and torturous course. For submandibular calculi, plain X-ray is the most useful initial study, as 80% are radio-opaque. In contrast, most parotid duct calculi are radiolucent. X-ray is considered the choice if clinical findings suggest stones are highly suspected. Otherwise, CT scan or ultrasound are used for initial assessment. (Option A) Ultrasound is increasingly used and can identify stones as small as 1 mm; however, it is difficult to perform in the submandibular area, especially where the lesion is away from the mandible. It is best used for parotid gland problems. (Option C) CT is complementary and can provide superior images in complex cases or recurrent disease. However, in some patients, artefacts from dental implants may limit usefulness. In most cases, CT scan and MRI are unnecessary. (Option D) MRI is not routinely used for diagnosis of sialadenitis and sialolithiasis. (Option E) A sialogram is useful for delineating the exact size and location of stones in a salivary gland duct. The stone will be visualized as a filling defect within the duct. Active infection of salivary gland is a contraindication for sialography because it can exacerbate the extent of the infection. While other means such as X-ray or CT-scan can be used, sialograms are less frequently used these days.`,
