    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Of the options, only decreased sensation of the lower leg can be specific to intervertebral disc prolapse and others can be manifestations of non-neurological problems as well. Radicular lower back pain can happen due to chemical or mechanical irritation of nerve roots. The pain is sharp, shooting, and has an electric quality. Unilateral leg pain is the more pronounced symptom and is often worse than pain in the back. Pain concentrates distally, running into the lower limb, usually extending below the knees. Pain, numbness, and paresthesia follow a dermatomal distribution. Reflexes may be reduced or even absent. Motor weakness is not always present. Lesions of the cauda equina can present with back pain, leg pain, paresthesia around the anus, and urinary incontinence. However, in this patient, the urinary problem is described as difficulty starting micturition and terminal dribbling, which is consistent with bladder outlet obstruction by causes such as an enlarged prostate. This patient's urinary problems (option A) are unlikely to have been caused by intervertebral disc prolapse. Although disc prolapse in the lumbar area can present with back pain (option C) and thigh pain (option B), such pain may have been caused by other factors than radiculopathy. Back pain may be due to a mechanical stressor. In fact, back pain is the common factor between mechanical and neural causes.`,
    reference: "amc",
    difficulty: "hard",
