    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `First-line treatment for patients with acute gouty arthritis is either potent NSAIDs such as indomethacin and naproxen or colchicine. The COX 2 inhibitor celecoxib is an acceptable but off-label option when NSAIDs are considered the first line, but the patient has a history of peptic ulcer disease, gastroesophageal bleeding, or gastritis. NOTE - Since celecoxib is not approved for gout treatment, it is better not to choose it as an option in the exam. In general, oral steroids, such as prednisone or intra-articular steroids, should be considered for patients who cannot tolerate or have contraindications to first-line medications. The recommended dose is 0.5mg/kg of prednisone (or equivalent) for 5 to 10 days with gradual dose reduction. Intra-articular steroid injection is the preferred method with only one affected joint and contraindications to first-line agents. Colchicine in reduced doses (not an option here) can also be used. For this patient with renal impairment, prednisone for ten days is the most appropriate option. (Option A) Allopurinol is a urate-lowering agent and is used to prevent further attacks of gouty arthritis. It should never be ceased during a gouty arthritis flare-up, as the resultant fluctuating serum urate level may worsen the condition. (Options B and C) NSAIDs such as indomethacin and the COX2 inhibitor celecoxib are contraindicated in patients with chronic kidney disease and should be avoided. (Option E) Increasing the allopurinol dose may be considered later to prevent further attacks, but it does not help treat acute flares. It is also recommended to avoid changing the dose of allopurinol in a patient who is already on it and has presented with an acute attack.`,
