    stem: `A 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a complaint of a red and severely painful right big toe. He has had such episodes in the same toe and the left big toe before. Based on the history, physical examinations, and laboratory tests, he is diagnosed with an acute attack of gouty arthritis. He is obese with a BMI of 32. He drinks 5 to 6 standard units of alcohol every day. He also has hypertension currently controlled on hydrochlorothiazide. His lab results include hypercholesterolemia, high LDL, low HDL, a serum creatinine level of 160 mmol/L (normal 50-110 mmol/L), and a serum uric acid level of 670 mmol/L (normal: 120-420 mmol/L). Which one of the following would you consider the first line for his treatment?`,
