    stem: `Jane is a 37-year-old woman who has presented to your clinic for the first time. She has a facial rash shown in the following photograph. According to her, the rash is more prominent when she is exposed to sunlight. She also complains of 4 kilograms weight loss in the past 3 months, occasional low-grade fever, and fatigue. She has had intermittent painful and mildly swollen wrists and knees to which recent finger pain has been added. On examination, oral ulcers that she has never noticed before are found. You order laboratory tests, which are remarkable for mild normocytic, normochromic anemia; mild thrombocytopenia; an elevated ESR of 110; positive ANA, and positive ds-DNA antibody. Which one of the following is the most appropriate long-term treatment option for her?`,
