    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `This man has presented with a clinical presentation that is very typical for lateral epicondylitis. Lateral epicondylitis is caused by degenerative changes of the wrist extensor muscles at their origin in the humeral lateral epicondyle. The extensor carpi radialis brevis muscle (ECRB) is the most commonly affected wrist extensor muscle. For patients with lateral epicondylitis, conservative management with activity modification to prevent further tendon overuse, counterforce bracing, and home-based exercises to strengthen the wrist extensor muscles is almost always the best initial management option. Persons with lateral epicondylitis should be instructed to modify their wrist and elbow movements in a way and direction that makes the palm face up rather than down to prevent or limit forearm pronation in which wrist extension can exert excess force on the wrist extensor tendons. However, this does not apply to all patients because their daily activity, including their job, entails typing or computer mouse use, during which the causative wrist and forearm movements are continued. For him, counterforce strapping decreased tension on wrist extensor tendons while he can continue his daily activities. Finger extension does not exert force on wrist extensor tendons; therefore, finger immobilization is not effective in providing rest for the wrist extensor tendons at the elbow. Use of paracetamol as non-prescribed analgesia has been used for the alleviation of pain in short term. However, advice for rest is not practical in this scenario as the nature of his job entails computer keyboard and mouse use, during which the causative wrist and forearm movements are continued. For him, counterforce strapping decreased tension on wrist extensor tendons while he can continue his daily activities. Immobilization of the elbow is inferior to counterforce bracing below the elbow in pain reduction and increasing strength of grip. Although controversial, short-term use of topical (or sometimes oral) non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) may be considered for acute and very painful cases. However, rest from the implicated activity using counterforce bracing remains the most appropriate initial option. An encircling support strap below the elbow acts as a counterforce brace for this patient and is the best choice among other options.`,
