    stem: `A 58-year-old woman presents to your GP clinic complaining of back pain that started suddenly after one hour of gardening. Her past medical history is unremarkable. She has been healthy and active until the event. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol in moderation. On examination, the lumbar spine's flexion, extension, and rotation are significantly limited, and tenderness between L4 and L5 is elicited. There is no tenderness over the vertebral bodies. After prescribing analgesics, which of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Bed rest.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Referral for orthopedic consultation.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Use of corsets.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Advise that she should maintain physical activity.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Magnetic resonance imaging of the lumbar spine.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Low back pain in the absence of alarming features is history and physical examination does not require specific management or evaluation other than reassurance, advising maintained physical activity, short-term use of analgesics, and review in 4 to 6 weeks. Physiotherapy may be considered for patients with protracted severe pain despite initial measures. Alarming features (red flags) are a set of signs, symptoms, or specific risk factors, the presence of which raise concerns regarding a serious underlying etiology for low back pain such as malignancies, infections, cord compression, cauda equina syndrome, etc. This occurs in approximately 1% of patients with acute low back pain. Red flags should be evaluated in the context of the clinical presentation as a whole, not as the sole guide for management because over 80% of patients with non-specific low back pain have a red flag in their histories irrelevant to their back pain. A high index of suspicion is raised when there is more than one red flag present. Although this woman is older than 50 years (a red flag), negative findings in the history and physical examination make such diagnoses weak possibilities. The age alone in this context is not a red flag justifying further assessment; imaging studies in particular. There are often abnormal findings on imaging studies of adults without low back pain which can make it difficult to correlate symptoms with imaging findings in patients with low back pain. Disc herniation is seen on MRI scans in 22 to 67% of asymptomatic adults and spinal stenosis in 21% of adults older than 60. Evidence of osteoarthritis is often seen on imaging but correlates poorly with the symptoms. Even when the radiographic findings are consistent with clinical presentation, the magnitude of radiographic findings does not necessarily correlate with clinical severity and outcome, and clinical improvement may not correlate with the resolution of the radiographic defect. For this woman, advising that maintaining physical activity is the best management option. She can take analgesics if the pain is bothersome. A review in 4 to 6 weeks should follow to see the response to treatment and further management planning.`,
    reference: "amc",
    difficulty: "medium",
