    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `When using a stick as a walking aid for problems of a lower limb (foot, ankle, knee, or hip), the stick should be held with the hand on the unaffected side (good leg) and the first step should be taken with the affected limb (bad leg). As this patient's problem is in his right leg, he should hold the stick with his left hand (the side of the good leg) and put his right foot (bad leg) forward first. When walking up stairs the good leg should take the first step and when walking down take the first step with the injured or affected leg.`,
